                  <p style="padding-top: 0px; " class="paragraph_style_14">Well, I say that, when [the body] has grown old, the [person’s mind is still firm] ...<br /></p>
                  <p style="padding-top: 0px; " class="paragraph_style_19"><br /></p>
                  <p style="padding-top: 0px; " class="paragraph_style_19">Fr. 142<br /></p>
                  <p style="padding-top: 0px; " class="paragraph_style_14">[For indeed the poets say that one who has grown old, although unable to be useful] with his body, [is champion in speech After he had encountered a recommendation of the] best [opinion, when Nestor spoke in the assembly, Agamemnon, according to Homer, said: «In truth, old man, once again you have outdone the sons of the Achaeans in debate»; and before meeting of the assembly, the king, so] the same [Homer says], «first seated a council of great-hearted elders». And there are others «through old age having ceased from war, but good speakers». [To the word of Homer is added that of the tragic poet Sophocles (?) ...]<br /></p>
                  <p style="padding-top: 0px; " class="paragraph_style_19"><br /></p>
                  <p style="padding-top: 0px; " class="paragraph_style_19">Fr. 143<br /></p>
